<a name="unit_intro"></a>
<h2>INTRODUCTION</h2>
The Heart: The Engine of Life is easy to use. All the instructions you will need to run the
program are in this Introduction. The rest of this Program Guide has hints to help
you better appreciate the program plus background information on healthy heart
function and heart disease.
<p>
The Heart: The Engine of Life is broken into 12 Units. You might find it helpful to read the
description of each Unit in this Program Guide before starting that Unit on the
computer. The Units are easier to understand if you look at them in
order.
<p>
<h3>INSTALLING AND STARTING THE PROGRAM</h3>
<p>
The Heart: The Engine of Life is distributed in one large "zip"
file, which means that all the information is compressed and collected 
into a single file for downloading.  The file name is THEHEART.ZIP and
it includes three versions of the program for three possible screen
resolutions.  To run it, you will also need an animation 'engine'
called P11RUN.EXE.  P11RUN.EXE is available worldwide in a file
called P11STUFF.ZIP.
<p>
THE HEART: THE ENGINE OF LIFE must be installed on your hard drive or 
on a floppy disk before it can be used.  Use PKUNZIP to decompress the 
program.  When you use PKUNZIP, you MUST use the parameters \ and -d 
because doing so will place the program in the \P11 directory, and in 
the subdirectory \P11\HEART.  
<p>
There are over 200 individual files comprising animations, text,
computer instructions, and sound effects in three screen modes. 
Therefore, we have organized everything under the \P11 directory and
have been doing so since 1984.  It may be placed on any drive but
must be in the \P11 directory.  Using PKUNZIP with the \ and -d
options will ensure the proper installation of THE HEART: THE ENGINE
OF LIFE on your system.
<p>
The format for PKUNZIP is:
<code> PKUNZIP.EXE  THEHEART.ZIP  d:/  -d</code>
<p>
where d: can be any drive (A: through Z:) or not be included.  The /
(foward slash) and -d (dash d) must be included to cause PKUNZIP to
create the directory structure.  This would unzip the complete
program.  
<p>
P11STUFF.ZIP is unzipped the same way and will place P11RUN.EXE in
the \P11 directory when it is finished.  TO unzip P11STUFF, use this:
<p>
<code> PKUNZIP.EXE  P11STUFF.ZIP  d:/  -d</code>
<p>
After installing The Heart: The Engine of Life it will be placed in 
a directory called \P11 on your hard drive. Go to the \P11 path.  
The DOS command to do that is:
<p>
<code>CD \P11)</code>
<p>
and type 
<p>
<code>RUN HEART</code>
<p>
This will run the RUN.BAT batch file from the \P11 directory, which
will actually start the program by running another batch file,
HEART.BAT, from the \P11\HEART directory.  HEART.BAT in turn runs
P11RUN.EXE, which is a universal animation engine.  For more
information about the animation engine that runs The Heart: The
Engine of Life, please visit our web site:
<p>
<code>http://www.animatedsoftware.com</code>
<p>
The program will automatically choose the highest of three screen
resolutions that it can run on your computer.  If you feel it has
chosen poorly, follow the instructions that appear on the <i>very
first screen</i> when you execute the RUN.BAT batch file.
<p>
When running the program you can exit at any time by
first pressing the <b>ESCAPE</b> key and then answering <b>Y</b> ( or
<b>y</b>) to the screen prompt that will appear.  <b>alt-q</b> (hold
the ALT key down and then while holding it down, pressing the Q key) will
also exit the program immediately.
<p>
There are three versions of The Heart: The Engine of Life.
The highest resolution version is 1024 by 768 dots and 256
colors, called SVGA mode 261.  The middle version is MCGA, which is
320 by 200 dots and 256 colors.  The low resolution version should run
on original 8088 IBM computers, and is 320 by 200 dots and 4 colors. 
Other than the loss of some color detail and/or some resolution
detail, the three versions are virtually identical.
<p>
After installation you can delete the \P11\HEART\CGAHEART path to
delete the CGA version or delete the \P11\HEART\MCGAHART path to delete the
VGA version, or delete the \P11\HEART\SVGAHART path to delete the
SVGA version, once you know which one your computer can use. 
However, we suggest you not do this, since sometimes adding new
hardware or software upgrades can cause the program not to run, at
least temporarily until you fully install something new.  Therefore,
we suggest you keep all three versions available so that the program
will probably always be there in one form or another when you want to
use it or show it to somebody.  Of course, you could always reinstall
it if you need to.
<p>
We urge you to make personal backup copies of the original ZIP file or
disks immediately. For your convenience they are not "copyprotected". 
<p>
<h4>
THE KEYBOARD
</h4>
<p>
The location and functions of the keys used in The Heart: The Engine of Life are shown in
Figure 1. When the program asks you to answer a question by pressing a number,
it is best to use the number keys at the top of the keyboard instead of those on the
numeric key pad, which are reserved for moving the cursor around the screen. (You
may use the numeric key pact by pressing NUMLOCK first, but then you will need
to press NUMLOCK again before using these keys to move your cursor.) The 
mouse can also be used for moving things around in many cases, but not all.
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmkey.gif" ALT="Image of Keyboard">
<p>
<b>Figure 1.</b>  
<i>Keys used in The Heart: The Engine of Life. The configuration of your keyboard may differ.
(The Function Keys are usuall above along the top, for instance.) 
<b>A:</b> Function
keys <b>F1</b>, <b>F2</b>, and <b>F3</b> are used throughout the program but only with onscreen prompts. At the
main menu, <b>F1</b> will give you a summary of operating instructions.
<b>B:</b> <b>F10</b> returns you to the
main menu.
<b>C:</b> <b>ESCAPE</b> (or <b>ALT-Q</b>) are used to exit the program.
<b>D:</b> The number keys
are used to answer questions and
to speed the action In Unit 4, The Broken Heart. <b>E:</b> The space bar, used only with on-screen
prompts. <b>F:</b> The <b>ENTER</b> key, used to confirm answers and advance the screen.
<b>G:</b> The cursor keys, used for a variety of tasks throughout the program.</i>
<p>
<h4>
THE MENU
</h4>
<p>
Figure 2 (below) shows The Heart: The Engine of Life main menu. In order to get into any of the program's
12 Units, you need to be at this menu. Press the number of the Unit you want to
see and then press <b>ENTER</b>. When you have viewed a Unit, the number of that
Unit will be highlighted when you return to the menu. This is to help you
keep track of what you've looked at and doesn't prevent you from getting into a
Unit twice or as many times as you'd like. When you are at the menu, press
<b>F1</b>
to get a summary of the operating instructions contained in this Introduction.
<p>
<h4>
GETTING TO THE MENU
</h4>
<p>
You can get back to the menu at any time from any Unit by pressing
<b>F10</b>. Use
<b>F10</b> when you're in the middle of one Unit and you want to leave it to go to another
Unit. When you want to take a second look at the beginning screens of a Unit which
you've already entered, press <b>F10</b> to get back to the menu and then reselect the
Unit you just left.  Although there are no "page up" or backspace capabilities 
in the program, each unit is relatively short.  
Other keys, such as <b>F1</b> and <b>ENTER</b>, can sometimes be used
to get back to the menu. When this is the case, you'll see instructions displayed on
the screen.
<p>
<h4>
EXITING THE PROGRAM
</h4>
<p>
To exit The Heart: The Engine of Life at any time, press <b>ESCAPE</b>. You will be asked first if
you are certain you want to exit. Press "<b>Y</b>" if you do and "<b>N</b>" 
if you don't want to
exit. If you press <b>ESCAPE</b>, you will be asked to press "<b>C</b>" 
to confirm your decision. "<b>C</b>" returns you to your machine's DOS. 
Alternatively, you can use <b>Alt-Q</b> to exit immediately to DOS.
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_engine"></a>
<h2>THE HEART: THE ENGINE OF LIFE</h2>
<p>
It is easy to forget how miraculous the human heart is. Hidden safely in the middle
of your chest, protected by your breastbone in front and your backbone in the rear,
the fist-sized muscle of your heart performs its constant labor unnoticed except in
moments of exertion or excitement. The more you consider the heart's prodigious
task, the more you will appreciate the wonder that beats within you.
<p>
The Heart: The Engine Of Life will show you the heart from a fresh perspective. 
These notes may help you to better understand some features of each Unit, but you may
enjoy it more if you view it first without reading these notes, and then view it again
after you have read them or while reading them.  We do not suggest you read 
each Unit in this text <i>prior</i> to viewing each unit.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Our imaginary island, "Humania", has a "Fuel Transport System" which is a 
good approximation of the body's
circulatory system. The arteries are shown in red on the top half of the body
and the veins are shown in blue on the bottom half. Notice when the system
is animated how all the "fuel" in the arteries moves away from the pump
and all the fuel in the veins moves toward it.
<p>
<li>
The red color of blood is due to its oxygen content. Notice in the capillary
net how the blood cells change from red to blue. This is because the blood
gives up some of its oxygen to feed the cells as it passes through the
capillaries. When you look at the veins in the back of your hand or wrist,
you can see that the blood has a bluish tinge because it has already carried
oxygen to your hand. Blood outside the body is always red because it
immediately picks up oxygen from the air.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_anatomy"></a>
<h2>THE HEART ANATOMY TUTORIAL</h2>
<p>
Although it sustains the immensely complex systems of the body, the heart itself
is a simple organ. It is, in essence, a hollow pear-shaped muscle divided into four
chambers. Each side of the heart has an upper chamber called an <i>atrium</i>, and a
lower chamber called a <i>ventricle</i>.
<p>
Blood flows into each atrium through a number of <i>veins</i>. From there, it 
flows into the ventricles and out of the heart through the <i>arteries</i>. 
There is a <i>value</i> between
each atrium and ventricle and between each ventricle and artery--four valves in all.
These valves only open in one direction to make sure that your blood keeps flowing
in one direction.
<p>
The flow of blood through the heart is covered in Unit 5, <b>The Heartbeat Tutorial</b>.
To prepare for that Unit, you should be able to identify and name:
<ul>
<li>1.) The <b>veins</b> which carry blood into the right or left side of the heart.
<li>2.) The four <b>chambers</b> which contract to keep blood moving through the
heart.
<li>3.) The four <b>valves</b>, which open only one way to keep the blood moving
in the right direction.
<li>4.) The <b>arteries</b>, which carry blood away from the heart.
</ul>
In <b>The Heart Anatomy Tutorial</b>, you learn the names of these important areas
by moving your cursor around a picture of the heart and asking each piece to
identify itself (see the instructions on the screen). Stay in this Unit for as long as
you Like.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
If you get a message saying "POSITION NOT RECOGNIZED. TRY AGAIN,"  
you are in an area that is too close to the border between two
different parts of the heart for the computer to decide which one you want
to identify. Move your cursor to a more distinct part to get a clear
identification.
<p>
<li>
<i>Pulmonary</i> means of or pertaining to the lungs. The pulmonary arteries
carry <i>deoxygenated</i> blood (blood which has little oxygen) to the lungs
where it picks up oxygen and releases carbon dioxide. The pulmonary
veins carry <i>oxygenated</i> blood (blood rich in oxygen) back to the heart so
that it can be pumped to the rest of the body.
<p>
<li>
The heart is the only area of the body where you find veins carrying blood
that is oxygenated and arteries carrying blood that is deoxygenated. Don't
let this confuse you. Just remember that veins carry blood to the heart and
arteries carry blood away from the heart.
<p>
<li>
The <i>mitral valve</i> got its name because it resembles a miter, a hat worn
by bishops. It is also referred to as the <i>bicuspid</i> valve, because it has two
cusps or folds of tissue that open and close. The <i>tricuspid</i> valve has three
cusps. The two valves together are known as the <i>atrioventricular</i> valves
because They lie between the atria and the ventricles.
<p>
<li>
The atria are sometimes referred to as auricles.
</ul>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmmen.gif" ALT="Image of Main Menu">
<p>
<b>Figure 2.</b>  <i>The Engine of Life Main Menu.</i>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
