<a name="unit_anatomyquiz"></a>
<h2>THE HEART ANATOMY QUIZ</h2>
<p>
Here is your chance to see how well you've learned basic heart anatomy. The
cursor moves in random order to each area that was identified in <b>The Heart
Anatomy Tutorial</b>. When the cursor stops, three names will be given. You must
select the correct name. At the end of the quiz, you'll be told how well you
performed. If you get more than five questions wrong, you may want to try the quiz
again or return to <b>The Heart Anatomy Tutorial</b> for more study.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
TAKE YOUR TIME! The names of some parts of the heart are very similar
and it's easy to leap at the wrong answer.
<p>
<li>
You must press <b>ENTER</b> to confirm your answer. If you accidentally press
the wrong number, use the backspace key to delete it.
</ul>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmopn.gif" ALT="Small open heart image">
<p>
<b>Figure 3.</b>  <i>A cut-away view of the heart.</i>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_broken"></a>
<h2>THE BROKEN HEART</h2>
<p>
This Unit tests your knowledge of the heart's anatomy and your skill at solving
puzzles. You meet Harvey Hardluck, an unfortunate man whose heart has broken
into pieces. These pieces correspond to the chambers, valves and blood vessels
used in <b>The Heart Anatomy Quiz</b>. Use your cursor keys to put Harvey's heart
back together. If you succeed, a brighter, happier Harvey will return to thank you.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
BE PRECISE! As in all forms of delicate surgery, close is not good enough.
You must place the piece <i>exactly</i> where it belongs. 
You can use the mouse to move the piece close to the proper location, 
then use the arrow keys on the keyboard to place them <i>exactly</i>.
The outline of the puzzle
and the outlines of the various pieces will help you to maneuver each piece
into its correct position. One clue: The pieces change color as they move
over other pieces. If you see two colors overlapping to create a third color,
then you know the piece isn't in place. If you see black between two pieces
that should fit right together, that's another sign that the piece is still out
of place.  
<p>
<li>
You don't have to select pieces in the order in which they're listed.
However, as in any jigsaw puzzle, it's hard if not impossible to know where
a piece should go if it's not along a border or connected to another piece
already in place. Use logic. Don't start out with a valve--you'll just be
guessing.
<p>
<li>
If you're wrong three straight times in guessing where a piece should be
placed, the program will make you try a new piece. The piece you failed
to place will be unavailable until you have placed another piece in
position.
<p>
<li>
You might want to time yourself and compare your speed with the time your
friends take to get Harvey's heart back together.
<p>
<li>
You can use the NUMBER keys to speed the movement. The cursor will
move up to ten spaces at a time, depending on what number you have
pressed. To use this feature, press a number key to set your speed (<b>1</b>
through <b>10</b>). When you're close to the exact location, press 
the <i>1</i> key and place the piece exactly.
<p>
<li>
If you're having a lot of trouble placing a piece, press 
Function Key 5 (<b>F5</b>) to automatically
put the piece in the correct position.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_heartbeat"></a>
<h2>THE HEARTBEAT TUTORIAL</h2>
<p>
The sequence of events that occurs with each heartbeat is known as the <i>cardiac
cycle</i>. <b>The Heartbeat Tutorial</b> describes the cardiac cycle in detail. At the end
of this Unit, you can use your cursor keys to control the rate of a beating heart.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Once you have gone through the cardiac cycle once, you can use Function Key 3 (<b>F3</b>)
key to animate the heartbeat. However, once you start the animation
sequence, you can't return to the step by step description of the heartbeat
unless you return to the main menu and select this Unit again.
<p>
<li>
Frequently, pictures showing the flow of blood through the heart show the
heart as though it is empty after each beat and then fills up before beating
again. Actually, the heart is always full. Although the amount of blood in
the heart varies at each stage of the cardiac cycle, <i>there is never empty
space or air</i>. If even a small bubble of air is introduced into the circulatory
system, it can cause severe damage to the body, even death, by causing
blood vessels to burst.
<p>
<li>
Blood going into the lungs through the pulmonary arteries travels through
smaller end smaller blood vessels until it reaches the <i>pulmonary capillaries</i>
(see Figure 4). The pulmonary capillaries cover microscopic air sacs, called
<i>alveoli</i>, at the ends of the bronchiole tubes. The walls of the alveoli and the
capillaries are very thin, thin enough to allow gases to pass through them.
Oxygen in the alveoli passes into the capillaries and is picked up by red
blood cells. The red blood cells in the capillaries release carbon dioxide
which passes into the alveoli and is exhaled. Oxygenated blood then flows
back toward the heart through larger and larger veins until it reaches the
right or left branches of the pulmonary arteries and the left atrium.
<p>
<li>
The valves of the heart are entirely passive. They open and close only in
response to the pressure of blood pushing up against them. There are
muscles attached to the atrioventricular valves called <i>papillary muscles</i>, but
these do not push the valves shut. Rather, they keep the valves from being
pushed back into the atria during ventricular contraction.
<p>
<li>
Your <i>heart rate</i>, the speed at which your heart beats, depends on a variety
of factors including age, sex, physical and mental activity, and health.
During exercise, when the body's demand for oxygen rises sharply, your
heart may beat at a rate as high as 180 to 200 beats per minute. When
you are frightened or excited, your body releases a hormone called
<i>adrenaline</i> which causes your heart to beat faster and harder to prepare you
for strenuous activity--the "fight or flight" response. Your <i>resting heart
rate</i> is tire rate at which your heart beats when you're physically and
mentally relaxed. Normal resting heart rates are very high in infants,
ranging from 100 to 160 beats per minute. Normal resting rates decline
steadily with age, reaching a low range of from 60 to 100 beats per minute
by the age of 20. Trained athletes may have resting rates as low as 40
because their hearts are strong and pump so much blood with each beat that
they don't need to beat as often.
<p>
<li>
The portion of the cardiac cycle during which your heart muscle is
contracting is called <i>systole</i>. The portion of the cycle when it is relaxed and
filling with blood is called <i>diastole</i>.
</ul>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmlng.gif" ALT="Alveoli">
<p>
<b>Figure 4</b>. <i>Respiration. Blood flowing from the heart to the lungs  (A) eventually reaches the capillaries
that cover the aveoli, or air sacs, of the lungs (B). Red blood calls traveling through these
capillaries (C) pick up oxygen from the alveoli and release carbon dioxide, which is then
exhaled.</i>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_spark"></a>
<h2>THE HEART'S SELF-GENERATING SPARK</h2>
<p>
Take your hand and start opening and closing it. Keep on doing this again and
again as though you were trying to crack a walnut. How long do you think you could
keep it up before your hand was too tired to work? Five minutes? Ten? Fifteen
at most? Consider, then, that your heart is working even harder than your hand
and will continue to work at this pace for as long as you live. Why is it that the heart
can exert such strenuous effort without resting for even a few seconds? The answer
lies in the special nature of cardiac muscle.
<p>
There are three types of muscle in the human body. <i>Smooth muscle</i> is found in
the linings of the digestive tract and blood vessels. The smooth muscles are
controlled by parts of your nervous system which you cannot consciously control.
<i>Skeletal muscle</i>, such as the muscle found in your arms and legs, can in most cases
be voluntarily controlled. Skeletal muscle is more able to perform fast and
strenuous work than smooth muscle. The third type of muscle is <i>cardiac muscle</i>,
the muscle which forms your heart. Cardiac muscle is similar in structure and power
to skeletal muscle, but like smooth muscle, it cannot be consciously controlled.
<p>
Unlike smooth muscle, cardiac muscle can contract without any signal from the
nervous system. Although the brain sends the heart messages to speed up or slow
down, the heart will continue to beat if all connections to the nervous system are
cut, provided it has a sufficient supply of oxygen and nutrients.
<p>
How does the heart beat all by itself? The answer lies within the smallest building
blocks of the human body--individual atoms. In an atom, the number of negative
particles (electrons) is equal to the number of positive particles (protons). When all
the particles are in place, the negative charge and the positive charge cancel out
each other and the atom as a whole has no charge. However, when an electron
is pulled away from the atom, the atom has more protons than electrons and a net
positive charge. Atoms which have an electrical charge are called <i>ions</i>.
<p>
Heart muscle cells contain positive ions of potassium, sodium and calcium. The
<i>membrane</i>, or wall, of each heart muscle cell has a natural tendency to "pump"
sodium and calcium ions out of the cell and pump potassium ions in. It pumps
sodium and calcium ions out at faster rate than it can pump potassium ions in.
Eventually, there are a lot more ions outside the cell than there are inside. Although
the cell has a positive charge, <i>it has a negative charge relative to its outside
surroundings</i>. The cell is <i>polarized</i>.
<p>
When the relatively positive charge outside the cell becomes too large, the flow of
ions suddenly reverses. Potassium ions rush out of the cell as sodium and
calcium ions rush in. The relatively positive charge is now <i>inside</i> the cell and the
cell is said to be <i>depolarized</i>. An imbalance exists once again, and that imbalance
is corrected when the cell resumes its tendency to pump potassium ions in and
sodium and calcium ions out. The cell is soon <i>repolarized</i>, and will stay that way
until the positive charge outside the cell again reaches a threshold and the flow once
again reverses. Every time this reversal of flow occurs, it generates a spark of
electricity which races through the heart. <i>It Is this electrical spark that causes
heart cells to contract and the heart to beat.</i>
<p>
<b>The Heart's Self-Generating Spark</b> is a graphic representation of minuscule
events which power the engine of Life.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Depolarization corresponds roughly with systole and repolarization occurs
towards the end of systole and the beginning of diastole.
<p>
<li>
There is never actually a moment in the cardiac cycle when all the potassium
in the heart is within the muscle cells and all the sodium and calcium is
outside the cell (or vice versa).
<p>
<li>
A single heart cell, placed in a laboratory dish with oxygen and nutrition to
sustain it, will beat.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_conducting"></a>
<h2>THE CONDUCTING SYSTEM</h2>
<p>
All the muscle cells in the heart have the ability to depolarize and start a wave of
contraction spreading out in all directions. However, if all the cells in the heart were
to "beat" at their own rate, the heart as a whole would quiver in a disorganized and
useless manner. To beat effectively, the heart needs order and rhythm, and both
these qualities are provided by the <i>conducting system</i>.
<p>
The conducting system consists of a network of specialized heart muscle cells that
function in a way similar to nerve cells. The function of the conducting system is
to 1) generate the electrical impulse which starts the cardiac cycle and 2) see that
the impulse spreads in an organized and rapid manner throughout the heart.
<p>
<b>The Conducting System</b> details the anatomy and function of the heart's
electrical network. You will need to be very familiar with this Unit if you wish to
attempt Unit 9--<b>Putting It All Together</b>.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
The <i>atrioventricular bundle</i> (AV bundle) is also known as the bundle of His
in honor of the man who discovered it.
<p>
<li>
The impulse generated by the conducting system reaches every muscle cell
in the heart and not just the cells of the conducting system itself. The
conducting system guides the spread of the impulse through the heart so
that every cell in the heart receives its signal to contract at just the right
instant.
<p>
<li>
The spread of the cardiac impulse through the heart shown in the program
corresponds closely to the actual path and timing of the impulse generated
by your heart, except it has been slowed down. In your heart, the impulse
generated by the <i>SA node</i> reaches the right edge of the left atrium in .03
seconds. It reaches the <i>AV node</i> in .04 seconds and the far edge of the left
atrium in .09 seconds. The impulse is delayed for more than .10 seconds
in the AV node, reaching the AV bundle .16 seconds after leaving the SA
node. From that point on, progress is extremely rapid. One-hundreth of
a second hater, the impulse reaches the <i>apex</i> of the ventricle and 
two-hundreths of a second later, It has spread up to the tops of the ventricles.
The impulse finally reaches the outer edge of the ventricular muscle mass
.22 seconds after it was generated.
<p>
<li>
The SA node is called the <i>pacemaker</i> because it depolarizes at a faster rate
than any other group of cells in the heart and imposes that faster rate on
the heart as a whole. If for any reason the SA node stops beating, the AV
node, which has the next fastest rate of depolarization, would become the
heart's pacemaker. If the AV node failed, the AV bundle would take over.
If it failed, the <i>Purkinje fibers</i> would start the heartbeat and if 
they failed as well,
a group of cells somewhere else in the heart would start pulsing. However,
the further away the heart gets from its normal pattern and rate of beating,
the less blood it pumps and receives, until eventually, it can no longer
sustain Life.
<p>
<li>
Disturbances in the heart's normal rhythm, known as <i>arrhythmias</i>, are one
of the most common forms of heart disease. Arrhythmias can be minor and
unimportant or severe and life threatening. There are many different kinds
of arrhythmias, including:
<ul>
<li><b>Tachycardia</b>, an abnormally fast heartbeat.
<li><b>Bradycardia</b>, an abnormally slow heart beat.
<li><b>Heart block</b>, which occurs when the electrical impulse has difficulty
passing through the AV node.
<li><b>Atrial flutter</b>, in which the atria contracts at rates of up to 180 beats
a minute.
<li><b>Ventricular fibrillation</b>, in which the ventricles contract in an irregular
and ineffective way, a condition which quickly leads to death unless
corrected.
</ul>
<li>
People who have serious arrhythmias can sometimes have an artificial
pacemaker implanted in their chests or abdomens. This battery powered
device delivers a rythmic electrical impulse to the heart on either a constant
basis or only when the heart's natural pacemaker temporarily fails to sustain
a normal beat.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_ekg"></a>
<h2>THE EKG</h2>
<p>
The <i>electrocardiograph</i> (EKG) is a machine that measures and records the
electrical activity of the heart. It is one of the most important tools doctors have
for diagnosing the health of the heart.
<p>
When an EKG is recorded, <i>leads</i> (electrodes--devices which can detect electricity)
are placed on the chest, the right and left wrists and the left ankle. The leads are
connected to the electrocardiograph which measures the positive and negative
currents detected by each lead and records the results as tracings on graph paper.
As many as twelve different leads may be used to gain different perspectives on how
the heart is functioning. An abnormality in the heart muscle or conducting system
may appear on the tracing of one lead yet not be detected by other leads. The
interpretation of EKG's is a skill which requires long study to learn.
<p>
<b>The EKG</b> describes the basic structure of an electrocardiogram and how each wave
in an EKG relates to events in the cardiac cycle. You must be familiar with the
information in this Unit if you wish to attempt the extra-credit exercise in Unit 9.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
The EKG pattern shown in this Unit is just one of the twelve different
patterns that can be obtained by using different leads. It is the pattern most
commonly used to demonstrate the principles of electrocardiography.
<p>
<li>
The first accurate electrocardiograph was designed by the Dutch physician
Willem Einthoven at the turn of the 20th Century. It used magnifying cameras
to record vibrations in a quartz filament which was attached to electrodes
strapped to a patient. Einthoven's EKG machine filled two rooms and needed
five people to operate it--a far cry from today's 30 lb. briefcase-sized
models. Still, this first EKG was so significant an achievement that it earned
Einthoven the Nobel prize in 1924.
<p>
<li>
The <i>QRS wave</i> is also know as the QRS complex. It is actually comprised
of three separate waves, the Q wave, the R wave and the S wave.
<li>
On some EKG's, a <i>U wave</i> can be seen. The U wave is small (it reflects a
small amount of electrical current) and occurs after the T wave and before
the P wave. It is caused by the repolarization of the papillary muscles which
are less conductive than normal heart muscle.
</ul>
<p><br>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmek1.gif" ALT="Ventricular tachycardia">
<p><br>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmek2.gif" ALT="Ventricular fibrilation">
<p><br>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmek3.gif" ALT="Atrial flutter">
<p><br>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmek4.gif" ALT="Atrial fibrilation">
<p><br>
<b>Figure 5.</b>  <i>EKG patterns of four arrhythmias. A: ventricular tachycardia, B: ventricular fibrilation, C: atrial flutter, D: atrlal fibrillation.</i>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_alltogether"></a>
<h2>PUTTING IT ALL TOGETHER</h2>
<p>
All your knowledge of the heart is tested in this Unit. You are asked to
integrate information about the heartbeat, the conducting system and the EKG
into a complete understanding of the cardiac cycle. <b>Putting It All Together</b>
is not a test or quiz but an exercise designed to improve your understanding of
the cardiac cycle. In the previous Units, you looked at the heart from one or
two different perspectives. In this Unit, you look at the heart from three
perspectives, comparing each to each.
<p>
<ul>This is how <b>Putting It All Together</b> works:
<li>1. Look at the pictures as they come onto the screen. The conducting
system is shown first, followed by the EKG and the beating heart. Each
picture will run through the cardiac cycle once before stopping. <i>Two
will stop at the same point in the cycle and one will stop at a
different point</i>.
<li>2.  Press the number of the picture that is at a stage in the cardiac cycle
which is <i>different from the stage of the other two</i>. (You don't need
to confirm your answer by pressing <b>ENTER</b>.)
<li>3. When you have selected the correct picture, it will start to move. When
it has moved to the same stage in the cardiac cycle as the other two
pictures, press the <b>SPACE BAR</b> to stop it. If you stop it at the wrong
stage, just press the <b>SPACE BAR</b> again and it will start moving. You
may stop and start the picture in this way as many times as you like.
<li>4. When you have stopped at the correct spot, press <b>ENTER</b> to confirm
your answer. If your answer is correct, press the <b>SPACE BAR</b> to move
on to the next question. If your answer is incorrect, press the <b>SPACE
BAR</b> to try again or press the "<b>?</b>" key to learn the correct answer.
</ul>
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
There is a moment between the end of repolarization and the
firing of the SA node when the conducting system graphic is blank.
<li>
When you are trying to stop a picture at the correct stage in the cardiac
cycle, be as precise as you can be. You don't have to be exact and stop
the picture on one particular dot. There are a series of correct
positions for each question.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="unit_heartattack"></a>
<h2>THE HEART ATTACK</h2>
<p>
The heart is the hardest working part of your body. Because it does more work than
any other muscle, it needs more oxygen and nutrients. Approximately five percent
of the blood the heart pumps is used to nourish the heart itself.
<p>
The heart supplies itself with blood through the coronary arteries. Two main
arteries, the right and left coronary arteries, branch off from the aorta just above
the aortic valve. These divide into smaller and smaller arteries that circle and
penetrate the heart, eventually reaching every one of the heart's muscle cells.
Because they are the heart's lifeline, the coronary arteries are also the body's
lifeline. When they become damaged, serious illness or death may result.
<p>
The most common disease to effect the coronary arteries is <i>atherosclerosis</i>,
commonly known as hardening of the arteries. Atherosclerosis occurs when the
inner wall of an artery becomes damaged, and fats such as cholesterol get inside
the artery walls. As the fat accumulates and hardens, there is less room for blood
to flow through the artery. <b>The Heart Attack</b> shows what can happen when the
coronary arteries become so damaged that the heart muscle can no longer receive
a sufficient supply of blood.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Atherosclerosis can affect any area in the body. When it strikes the heart,
it is called <i>coronary artery disease</i>. When it strikes the blood vessels which
serve the brain, it may result in a <i>stroke</i>, a loss of brain function due to a
cutoff in the brain's oxygen supply. Strokes may be mild, severe or fatal.
The aftereffects of a stroke depend on which area of the brain suffers the
loss of oxygen and for how long. Symptoms include paralysis, loss or
slurring of speech, partial or complete loss of sight, and memory loss.
Factors which influence the development of atherosclerosis and coronary
artery disease are discussed in <b>The Heart Risk Factor Lab</b>.
<p>
<li>
People at risk for heart attacks frequently experience chest pain known as
<i>angina pectoris</i> ("pain in the chest"). Angina attacks occur when a portion
of the heart muscle is not receiving enough oxygen. The typical attack lasts
from one to ten minutes and is usually brought on by exercise, emotional
stress, overeating, or any activity which causes the heart's demand for
oxygen to increase beyond the ability of the narrowed coronary arteries to
deliver it. The angina pain subsides with rest. The crucial distinction
between an angina attack and a heart
attack is that in a heart attack, the reduction in blood flow is so acute or
prolonged that heart muscle cells die.
<p>
<li>
The capacity of the coronary arteries to carry blood must be reduced to 30
to 40 percent of normal before angina symptoms appear.
<p>
<li>
Even if as much as 25 percent of the left ventricle's muscle dies in a heart
attack, the heart may still be able to recover.
<p>
<li>
The severity of a heart attack depends on the size of the <i>infarction</i> (dead
tissue) and its location. Death may result from a variety of causes. If the
conducting system is damaged, the heart may go into ventricular fibrillation,
a disorganized quivering of the heart muscle which leaves the heart unable
to pump enough blood to sustain life. If too much muscle is destroyed, the
heart may still beat but without sufficient force to meet the body's needs.
This condition is know as heart failure. If part of the heart is severely
damaged, this part may rupture and allow blood to flow out into the chest
cavity, a disaster which leads quickly to death. Approximately 15 to 25
percent of heart attacks are fatal. In over half of fatal heart attacks, the
victim does not reach a hospital in time to receive life-saving emergency
treatment.
<p>
<li>
After a nonfatal heart attack, the dead tissue turns into <i>scar tissue</i>, dense,
hard connective tissue that no longer beats or conducts electricity. If the
scar tissue is small enough and not located along the conducting system, the
heart may recover to normal or near normal strength. If the scar tissue is
large or located in an important area, it will reduce the effectiveness of the
heartbeat and may disrupt the heart's natural rhythm.
</UL>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_bypass"></a>
<h2>THE BYPASS OPERATION</h2>
<p>
When x-rays of the coronary arteries show that these arteries are seriously blocked,
doctors may recommend a <i>coronary bypass operation</i>. In a bypass operation,
doctors 1) take a vein from the leg, 2) connect one end of this vein to the aorta, and
3) connect the other end of the vein to a spot beyond the blockage in the coronary
artery. The "new" vein bypasses the blockage and allows blood to reach the muscle
beyond it.
<p>
The operation was made possible by the development of the heart-lung machine.
The machine oxygenates the blood and keeps it moving during surgery so that the
heart can be momentarily stopped to allow surgeons to work on it. Heart bypass
surgery is only recommended when severe pain due to angina does not respond
well to medication or when a person has a very high risk of a heart attack due to
severely obstructed coronary arteries.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Approximately 50,000 coronary bypass operations are performed each
year in the U.S.. Most of the patients receiving the operation require more
than one bypass graft. Eighty to 90 percent of the patients receiving this
operation have some or all of their angina pain relieved. The operation,
however, is not a cure for coronary artery disease. It will not stop other
arteries in the heart, or even the new arteries grafted onto the heart, from
developing new blockages.
<p>
<li>
Physicians are constantly searching for ways of treating coronary artery
disease that are less "invasive" than bypass surgery--techniques that don't
involve opening the patient's chest and operating directly on the heart. A
number of other procedures look promising. In one procedure called
<i>coronary angioplasty</i>, a deflated balloon is snaked into the coronary
arteries until it reaches an area where <i>plaque</i> (built-up fat) is blocking the
flow of blood. The balloon is then inflated and the plaque is flattened against
the wall of the artery, leaving more room for blood to pass. Doctors also
expect to soon be using lasers to destroy plaque. Experiments in animals
show that laser beams can be fired through a catheter inserted into the
coronary arteries to safely blast plaque away a little at a time.
</ul>
<p>
<a href="#program_guide">Top of Guide.</a>
<hr>
<a name="unit_risks"></a>
<h2>THE HEART RISK FACTOR LAB</h2>
<p>
During the Korean War, doctors were surprised to find that the hearts of many
young men killed in battle had already begun to develop coronary artery disease.
Their discovery helps to illustrate that <i>you're never too young to start thinking
about the health of your heart and to start developing habits that will reduce
your risk of developing heart disease</i>. The health of your heart is a lifetime
responsibility. The best way to start accepting that responsibility is by becoming
more familiar with the factors that increase your risk of developing coronary artery
disease. That is the purpose of <b>The Heart Risk Factor Lab</b>.
<p>
<b>HEREDITY</b>. Heredity is an important factor in determining your likelihood of
developing coronary artery disease. Although nothing can be done about heredity,
it is very important to appreciate the risks of hereditary factors. If you know you're
at increased risk because heart disease runs in your family, you have all the more
reason to take steps to reduce other preventable risk factors.
<p>
<b>SMOKING</b>. Smoking is the largest preventable cause of death in America. Each
year, roughly 350,000 Americans die because they were smokers.  <i>The majority
of these deaths, two-thirds, are not due to cancer, but to heart disease.</i> If you
smoke, you have approximately five times as great a risk of dying of coronary heart
disease than if you don't smoke.
<p>
Smoking damages the heart in a number of ways. It makes a person far more likely
to develop coronary artery disease. It stimulates the development of blood clots
which can block narrowed or even healthy arteries, leading to strokes and heart
attacks. Cigarette smoke contains carbon monoxide which competes with oxygen
and reduces the amount of oxygen your blood can carry. This forces your heart
to work harder to pump more blood. Smoking may also cause blood vessels to go
into spasms, clamping shut and cutting off blood flow to the heart and other
essential organs.
<p>
<b>CHOLESTEROL</b>. The danger of cholesterol was first considered after World War
II. Doctors noticed that the rate of heart attacks decreased dramatically in areas
suffering shortages of food high in cholesterol--meat, eggs and cheese. After the
war, the number of heart attacks increased to prewar levels. A suspicion arose that
heart attacks may be caused in part by a diet high in fats. Studies since the war have
shown that people with high cholesterol levels definitely have more heart attacks
than people with low or normal levels.
<p>
Cholesterol causes heart attacks by accumulating in the walls of the coronary
arteries. Not everyone who eats foods rich In cholesterol develops high cholesterol
levels--more than 220 milligrams per deciliter (1/10 liter). Some people don't hold
on to cholesterol, no matter how much they eat, while others can get high
cholesterol levels from eating only moderate amounts of this fat. The good news
is that high cholesterol levels can be controlled by diet. A diet low in cholesterol
results in lower levels of cholesterol in the blood and decreases the risk of coronary
artery disease.
<p>
<b>WEIGHT</b>. Statistics show that people who are significantly overweight (more than
20 percent) have an increased risk of developing coronary artery disease. Excess
weight puts excess strain on the heart. It has been estimated that for each additional
pound a person gains, the body must build 200 more miles of blood vessels to
nourish the additional tissue. The extra weight also increases the risk of developing
high blood pressure which is another risk factor (see below).
<p>
<b>PERSONALITY</b>. Many doctors now believe that personality traits can influence
the likelihood of developing coronary artery disease. Researchers have noticed that
a certain type of individual, called a <i>Type A</i> person, is more likely to develop
coronary artery disease than another type of individual, called a <i>Type B</i> person.
<p>
Type A people constantly feel under pressure. They are always in a rush, always
thinking about what they have to do next, always pushing themselves. They find
it difficult to relax either physically or mentally. Type B people have a more relaxed
attitude and take life in stride. They are not apt to rush, or rather, to feel rushed
and they are generally satisfied with life. The principle difference between Type
A and Type B people has nothing to do with accomplishments or productivity. It
has to do with attitude, how they feel about life and how they approach it.
<p>
<b>BLOOD PRESSURE</b>. Blood pressure is the amount of force your blood exerts
against the walls of your arteries. It is usually expressed by two numbers e.g. 120/80, 
or 120 over 80--where the first number is a measurement of the pressure in
your arteries during systole and the second number is the pressure in your arteries
awing diastole. The systolic pressure is always higher than the diastolic pressure
because after each heartbeat, there is more blood in your arteries and therefore
more pressure.
<p>
High blood pressure, also called <i>hypertension</i>, occurs when pressure in the arteries
rises above normal levels. In general, anyone with blood pressure higher than 140/90 
is considered to have hypertension. Doctors aren't sure what causes high blood
pressure, but they do know that people who have it also have an increased risk of
developing heart disease and having strokes. Some studies show that people with
high blood pressure have two or more times the risk of having a heart attack. The
reason for this increased risk is not yet known, although some doctors believe that
the increased pressure damages the arterial walls and leads to atherosclerosis. High
blood pressure can be controlled in most patients by reducing salt intake, losing
weight if necessary, and taking medications.
<p>
<h4>GOOD TO KNOW:</h4>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
Answer all questions as honestly as possible. Don't be tempted to give the
"right" response. The only right response is an accurate response.
<p>
<li>
When you press the <b>UP ARROW</b> key to record your height, you will see
a yellow line along the height markings. Hold the arrow down to
make the line move faster. Each press of the arrow moves the height up
by one-fifth of an inch, so you can be very precise. If you overshoot your
correct height, use the <b>DOWN ARROW</b> key to adjust your answer before
pressing <b>ENTER</b>. Likewise, when recording your weight, you'll see a
yellow line appear along the weight markings when you press the <b>RIGHT
ARROW</b>. Hold it down to make it go faster and use the <b>LEFT ARROW</b> to
make any corrections. Each press of these arrows changes the weight by
one pound.
<p>
<li>
There is some debate as to whether or not a person can be considered
overweight without being fat. Many athletes, for example, may be 30 to
40 percent over the desirable weight for their height yet have a lower
percent of body fat than many who aren't overweight.
</ul>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM SRC="hrtsmgra.gif" ALT="Double Bypass">
<p>
<b>Figure 6.</b>  <i>A double bypass. Veins have been grafted from the aorta to bypass blockages 
in the right and left coronary arteries.</i>
