<header>
<title> Unzipping "P11" applications when you use America Online</title>
</header>
<body>
<hr>
<h3> How to unzip and install "P11" programs when using AOL </h3>
<h2>This information is only useful for people who find our software
on a forum on AOL and are using AOL for downloading. </h2>
<hr>
<a href="/ascodesc/ascodesc.htm"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=5 WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=14 SRC="/pics/icons/ascologo.gif" ALT=""></a>
<p>
<hr>
A new user on AOL sent us the following question, which we have
answered in great detail...  (or, everything you ever wanted to know
about downloading P11 programs while using AOL.)  
<p>
<i>Help! My first time in downloading and I want to make sure I am doing IT
right. I want to download How animation works and The Demo of the heart.
Please send the proper tools I need; they talk about p11stuff?</i>
<p>
The way downloading usually works is that you download "files" which have
been compressed (also called zipped.  They are shrunk or made smaller).  The
main reason files are compressed is so that they download more quickly.
That's the only reason, but it's an important one!  However, another reason
one might compress something is that the file actually consists of many files
which are brought together and shrunk down as small a possible (compressed)
into one file.
<p>
Almost all of ours, for example, are like that.  The demo of the heart is ten
or twelve separate files which are decompressed (or unzipped) onto your hard
drive and then they can be run.  The How to Make Animation program is also
several files all zipped together.
<p>
So that's what you are downloading. 
<p>
Our company actually offers something like 600 or 1000 separate files for
you, for free, through America Online.   These are zipped up into 30 or so
files for download, such as the two you've selected.  We are BIG supporters
of AOL and like to offer lots of really useful demos.  In fact, we are
actually the oldest company with continuous online support in the graphics
forum. 
<p>
Anyway, all these educational animations all need the same animation engine
to run--that's what the P11 thing is.  Officially called RUSSELL's "P11"
ANIMATION MACHINE, there is an editor version and a runtime version.  The
editor version is used to create educational software.  The runtime version
is used to run things.  So the demos we offer, including the two you've
selected, need the runtime version, which is in a file called P11STUFF.ZIP.
It is available from our Internet web site or might also be found on AOL
somewhere.
<p>
Because we offer so many files, and because thousands of people download more
than one demo (as you did) we feel it is useful to organize everything after
it's downloaded, on your hard drive.  So, everything from our company is
designed to be placed in one directory (and many subdirectories) on your hard
drive.  That directory is \P11 and it can be on any drive. 
<p>
The \P11 directory is automatically created whenever you unzip any of our
files using PKUNZIP with the \ and -d options, like this for example:
<p><code><b>
PKUNZIP.EXE  P11STUFF.ZIP  C:\  -D
<p></b></code>
This would unzip the file P11STUFF (which contains P11RUN.EXE) to the \P11
directory on the c: drive.
<p>
Lastly, when AOL downloads things it can automatically decompress them.
You can turn this "feature" off using PREFERENCES in AOL, and we
recommend you do that for our products. The reason:
Unfortunately AOL won't recreate the directory structure <i>at the root
level</i> so the \P11 directory might exist (depending on what version of AOL you are
using) but it will be in, for example, the \aol25\download\amazing directory. 
AOL creates a directory in \aol25\download with the name of the file, in this case
<b>amazing.zip</b>, and then creates the subdirectory structure under it.
<p>
This won't run our programs properly, but it's fairly easy to fix so it will.  You
can do one of two things.  First, simple manually unzip the files again using
PKUNZIP and the options given above.  Then delete the \<i>filename</i>\P11 directory tree
under \aol25\download\.   
<p>
The other way is to use the <b>DOS</b> command XCOPY, like this:
<p><code><b>
xcopy \aol25\download\p11stuff\p11\*.*  c:\p11\*.* /s
<p></b></code>
This will copy everything created automatically be AOL if you have it set to
automatically decompress everything it finds in the \aol25\download directory
when you sign off.  If you let it decompress our files, it creates (at least,
version WAOL 2.5 does this) the \p11 directory and the subdirectories, but it
does this underneath the \aol25\download\<i>filename</i>\ directory!  This is quite
useless since we can't put everything under the \p11 directory this
way--instead, there is a \p11 directory created for each file you download.
Hence, the need to use the DOS XCOPY command or to reunzip the files.
<p>
I know this is a long answer, but I think it's pretty complete.  If you still
have trouble, please email me again and I'll try to help.  May I also suggest
you try our file FIVEHORS.ZIP?  This is an interesting animation of five
horses in different gaits, and it contains everything needed to run in one
file, making it a little easier to download and try.  In fact, to test that I
had all my facts right for this email I downloaded it (and all the files you
downloaded as well) and ran it just a paragraph or two ago!
<p>
<hr>
<p>
We thought this was everything you needed to know.  It wasn't.  The user responded with this:
<p>
<i>
I am on the newest AOL version. In order for me to download any of your
animation files I need to download (hitting the download Button) p11stuff.zip
first, Correct? Then go ahead and download How animation works? Where do I go
after to retrieve this information so I can use this, or even transfer it
onto my disk? 
<p>
I did appreciate your last reply and was very helpful. Being new at this I
want to make sure I do this right. I am doing a class presentation on
computer animation but more importantly learning for myself on the creation
of animation.
</i>
<p>
(Our response follows...)
<br>
<p>
You need P11STUFF.ZIP for most, but not all, or our animations and you need
it specifically for the two you downloaded (AMAZING.ZIP and P11-EDUC.ZIP, if
I remember correctly).  There are some--for example FIVEHORS.ZIP and
GENI.ZIP--where P11RUN.EXE is included.  For those, you don't need to
download P11RUN.EXE (which is in P11STUFF.ZIP, as mentioned in my previous
letter.)
<p>
Note that even if you've downloaded one of the self-contained ones like
FIVEHORS.ZIP you should still go ahead and download P11STUFF.ZIP because it
contains a batch file (soon to be simply another P11 demo, by the way) which
runs ALL our files.  It's called RUN.BAT, by the way.  Each application has a
specific batch file for its own operation, too.  RUN.BAT simply calls
those batch files--it never executes P11RUN.EXE itself.    
<p>
Sooner or later (soon I hope!) we will move to a master P11 screen that
introduces all the demos (perhaps even decompresses them for you too), at
which point RUN.BAT <i>will</i> simply execute P11RUN.EXE.  This is something that
has been suggested to me repeatedly over the years but I just didn't get
around too.  Now, with everything usually starting in Windows, (and having
been downloaded) it really makes sence to simplify this whole process that
way--or some way!
<p>
So, to answer your first question, yes.  You do need to click on DOWNLOAD NOW
button or the DOWNLOAD LATER button to download a file.  Next will display a
window suggesting you place the file in the \AOL25\DOWNLOAD directory.  You
can change it to a different directory but each time you download something,
it asks again if you want it here.  So, most people, I'm sure, put it here
(in the \aol25\download directory).
<p>
The download process transfers the compressed files to your disk.  The next
step is to decompress them (also to your disk).  This can be done
automatically with AOL's software, and that is not a bad way to do it.  If
you choose to let AOL downcompress it, then you need to use XCOPY afterwards
to copy the entire subdirectory structure, starting at the \P11 level and as
described in my previous coorespondance, to the \P11 directory at the root
level.  See my previous email for the exact syntax of the necessary DOS XCOPY
command.
<p>
Where do you execute XCOPY?  (or PKUNZIP, the alternative method to use if
you don't let AOL decompress the files, as also described yesterday)
<p>
You execute these commands, XCOPY or PKUNZIP, from the DOS command line while
in the \aol25\download directory.   
<p>
Use the DOS command cd (Change Directory) to go to the \aol25\download
directory, like this:
<p>
<code>
cd\aol25\download
</code>
<p>
that will put you in the \aol25\download directory, which is where all the
files you ever download go in AOL, unless you override that feature.
Frankly, I wish AOL decompression software would simply give you the option
to recreate the directory structure in the files you download and decompresss
AT THE ROOT LEVEL, but they don't, so you need to either use XCOPY and move
the thing, or don't let AOL decompress it and use PKUNZIP with \ and -d
options.
<p>
I hope this answers you additional questions but please don't hesitate to ask
more.  It's been kind of fun to analyze the whole procedure so carefully for
you.  There are certainly a lot of steps involved, and so many of them a
"pro" takes for granted, like being able to find the download button!  You
may be interested to know that I've taken our first correspondance and
placed it at my web site (I didn't use your name, only your question(s) and
my answer(s)) and I'll do the same with this one, so that perhaps others will
be able to get through this part more easily next time.  
<p>
So ask away!  I will get you watching animated horses and hearts, and
learning how to animate on your own soon!  I won't give up if you won't.
<p>
<hr>
Note:  You can also simply decompress most P11 applications from THE ANIMATED
SOFTWARE COMPANY into any directory, and the batch file that starts
the program will look for P11RUN.EXE in the \P11 directory and in the current directory.
However, if you use the parameters given above to recreate our
directory structure, you will be able to use the RUN.BAT master batch
file most of the time.
<p>
<hr>
<br>
