<header>
<title> Specs for my Mountain Bike</title>
</header>
<body>
<hr>
<h1> Specs for my Manitou System FS! </h1>
<hr>
<p>
I ride a 19" Answer Manitou System FS Full Suspension Mountain Bike.  I keep it with a Kryptonite
New York Lock and motorcycle-type 5/8's inch braided cable.  Bike was
purchased used from Cantina Bikes, Sorrento Valley and is now cared for by
the good folks at Cycle World, Carlsbad, California.
<p>
<ul><b>Exact Specs for my bike:</b>
<li> Answer Manitou System FS 19" Aluminum frame, c. 1993 
<li> Manitou Mach V SX Front Suspension with 61mm travel (Upgraded from stock Manitou III)
<li> Manitou III Rear Suspension (Upgraded elastomers)
<li> Answer Hyperlite 3 degree Handlebar (Blue)
<li> King Head Set
<li> Ringl&eacute; Stem
<li> Ringl&eacute; Anti-Chainsuck Thing, Dremeled to fit more precisely (and sometimes it actually works.)
<li> Third Eye Chain Watcher
<li> Bullet Bros. Chain Tensioner, Dremeled to fit better
<li> Syncros Titanium Bottom Bracket
<li> Topline Cranks 
<li> Panaracer Green Lites Inner Tubes <!-- upgraded from Specialized light-weight rubber compound.-->
<li> Panaracer Magic Kevlar Tires 
<li> Mavic 217 Wheels with steel spokes  <!--(Upgraded from Richie Vantage Wheels) -->
<li> Salsa Skewers and Seatpost Quick-release (Ti front skewer and seatpost skewer, steel rear skewer)
<li> Shimano XTR Front Hub  <!--(Upgraded from Shimano) -->
<li> Shimano XTR Rear Hub  <!--(Upgraded from Shimano) -->
<li> Shimano Deore XT Rear Derailleur with booster aftermarket spring somewhere inside it
<li> Shimano Deore XT Front Derailleur with Manitou clamp modification
<li> Avid 22T Steel chainring <!--upgraded from Suntour Summer 1996-->
<li> Real 32T Nickle-plated Aluminum Chainring <!--(Upgraded from Suntour) -->
<li> Shimano Hyperdrive Large Chainring <!--(Upgraded from Suntour) -->
<li> Shimano XT Rear Cassette  <!--(Upgraded from Shimano) -->
<li> Shimano XTR V-Brake Levers  <!--(Upgraded from Diacomp) -->
<li> Shimano XTR V-Brakes.  <a href="/mtnbikes/reviews/myvbraks.htm">V-brakes really are amazing</a>. <!--(Upgraded from Diacomp 987's) -->
<li> Plastic grease slots on both brake cable housings
<li> Shimano XTR Rapidfire Shifters  <!--upgraded from Shimano -->
<li> Titanium Crankbolts  <!--upgraded from Aluminum -->
<li> Topeak/Potts USA Survival Gearbox toolkit on seatpost<!--upgraded from Cool Tool Summer 1996 -->
<li> Spare Greenlite Tube and both kinds of patch kits (Greenlite and regular rubber)
<li> BTU Stokers and/or:
<li> Power Bars
<li> A Helmet, <i>every time</i>
<li> Thickly Padded Gloves
<li> Hard elbow pads
<li> TruFit Knee pads with the holes in the back
<li> Specialized shoes
<li> Nishiki stock plastic pedals with leather straps, off my old Nishiki Arroyo which was stolen
out of my garage a week after I bought my Manitou.  But they <i>couldn't
cut the chain</i> that held the Manitou and they didn't know enough to strip the parts off it. 
Anyway, these Nishiki pedals are tough as nails and take hits
beautifully.  They are my original pedals from around 1992 and have
taken hundreds of rock hits.  
<li> Lycra pants by Urbaneck.  These have taken a few rock hits as well...
<li> Johnson & Johnson bandages
<li> Neosporin Antibacterial Ointment
<li> Sunscreen lotion, SPF 30 or higher, hypo-allergenic
<li> Insect Repellant, hypo-allergenic
</ul>
