<head>
<title>Exec. Council Statement on Sexual Harassment</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2>AFL-CIO Executive Council<br>
May 9, 1996<br>
Statement</h2>
<h1 align="center">Sexual Harassment</h1>
<p align="center"><em>The AFL-CIO reaffirms its condemnation of
sexual harassment as an illegal violation of human dignity.</em> </p>
<p>The number of sexual harassment claims filed with the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) in 1993 was more than
double the number filed in 1990. Ninety percent of harassment
cases involved men harassing women, nine percent involve same sex
harassment and one percent involve women harassing men. Surveys
show that a large portion of working women have been sexually
harassed at work, with figures ranging from 40 percent to 65
percent. The AFL-CIO must continue to work to prevent harassment
and other forms of sex discrimination through education,
enforcement of strong policies and state and federal laws and by
fostering an environment that supports working women.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../estatement.html">Executive Council Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
