<html>
<head>
<title>2/19-Exec Council Statement on Organizing Power</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>                                                AFL-CIO Executive Council
                                                        February 20, 1996
                                                                Statement
</pre>
<h3 align="center">Building Power for Workers By Organizing </h3>
<p>The crisis of a declining union movement is the crisis of
workers in America. All working families have been affected. The
middle class is in free fall. Economic anxiety is pervasive.
Average hourly wages have been dropping since 1973 and real
family income is lower than it was twenty years ago. </p>
<p>For low wage workers, women and people of color, the news has
been even worse. And the gap between rich and poor is growing. </p>
<p>Our loss has meant gains for employers: </p>
<ul>
    <li>For the first time since the Depression increased worker
        productivity has not been followed by a rise in incomes. </li>
    <li>Corporate profits are at a forty-five year high. </li>
    <li>Wealth is more concentrated at the top than at any time
        in the last 25 years. </li>
    <li>Temporary and part-time work at low wages without
        benefits now accounts for most of the job growth in our
        economy. </li>
</ul>
<p>Elections of the last decade have delivered political
leadership with a non-union vision for Americats future. Gains
won by a more powerful labor movement, like minimum wage, health
and safety projections, even Social Security are greatly eroded
or in jeopardy. </p>
<p>There are many reasons for the decline in union membership.
Federal labor law has failed to protect workers' rights to
organize unions and bargain collectively with their employers.
Most workers seeking to gain power by organizing must run a
gauntlet of fear created by employer anti-union campaigns. </p>
<p>Other forces have also eaten away at the organized base: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Many unionized companies have moved overseas in search of
        low-wage workers or pared their work forces by
        contracting out jobs or using temporary employees. </li>
    <li>New technologies have eliminated jobs in basic industry;
        new industries with unorganized work forces have emerged. </li>
    <li>Government at every level has responded to cost pressures
        by replacing decent union jobs with lower wage and
        benefit &quot;privatized&quot; jobs. </li>
</ul>
<p>This has only encouraged assaults by increasingly greedy and
control-driven employers. Union members have held onto more gains
than working families overall, but the incentive to attack has
been increased as the cost gap between union work and nonunion
work has widened to more than 20%. </p>
<p>We cannot simply hold on to what we have. Organized labor will
be bigger or smaller. The decision rests with us. </p>
<p>Unless a broad, serious effort is launched to dramatically
increase resources to re-establish power in the labor market,
workerst power will continue to erode. </p>
<p>In recognition of these challenges, the Federation should work
closely with the unions to rebuild the labor movement by: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Providing leadership, coordination and support for a
        movement-wide effort to return unions to a dominant role
        in improving the lives of Americans; </li>
    <li>Promoting efforts to refocus unions at all levels on
        organizing and dramatically increase spending on
        organizing; </li>
    <li>Helping develop the internal capacity of unions to
        increase the scale of organizing and membership education
        programs about the necessity to organize; </li>
    <li>Assisting in the development of strategic plans and
        leverage strategies; </li>
    <li>Assisting in recruiting and training a new generation of
        organizers; </li>
    <li>Promoting and coordinating the integration of political,
        legislative and legal activity, bargaining strategies,
        and corporate strategies to increase unions' ability to
        organize, and; </li>
    <li>Raising the visibility and public profile of unions as
        the vehicle for improving the jobs, working conditions
        and lives of American families. </li>
    <li>Expansion of bargaining unit strength by increasing
        membership levels in existing units and by using
        bargaining leverage to create organizing opportunities,
        including neutrality and card check provisions. </li>
</ul>
<p>To accomplish these goals the Federation should, through its
organizing program; encourage and assist unions to increase
spending on organizing at all levels; encourage and assist unions
in developing and winning large scale organizing campaigns;
encourage and assist unions in organizing that seeks to represent
entire industries or geographic areas; and advance and develop
the skills and capabilities of the organizing programs of union
internationals and locals. </p>
<p>Therefore the organizing program of the AFL-CIO should focus
on these areas: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Increasing resources to organizing and targeting efforts
        to increase the labor movement's capacity to recruit and
        train organizers. </li>
    <li>Working with unions to develop a consensus among local
        and regional leaders, as well as members, for the
        necessity to spend more on organizing at all levels and
        to address the consequences of that decision within their
        unions. </li>
    <li>Offering strategic campaign assistance to unions in the
        development and execution of expanded organizing
        campaigns. </li>
</ul>
<h4>Program Description</h4>
<p>The department program will seek to fulfill these objectives
by implementing these three programs: </p>
<p>Organizing Institute: Efforts to recruit and train organizers
will involve recruitment of rank and file union members and
direct recruitment of young people on college campuses. The
institutets field training program will directly assist unions in
running large campaigns by providing field training interns and
apprentices and experienced field trainers to assist in
campaigns. The Organizing Institute will also seek to develop on
an experimental basis new models of recruitment and training such
as Union Summer '96. </p>
<p>Restructuring to Organize: This program will expand on its
initial work with local and regional elected leaders wishing to
refocus and restructure their unions to do more organizing and do
it more successfully. By providing forums where elected leaders
can discuss the needs and problems of changing their institution
to dramatically increase organizing spending and success with
their peers, the program has provided a unique opportunity to
&quot;take stock&quot; and rethink both the needs and directions
of their unions. Success will be measured by increases in
spending and organizing victories. </p>
<p>Strategic Campaign Assistance: The Federation will encourage
and assist new organizing that can make a significant
contribution to the expansion and development of organizing
programs. Innovative organizing approaches will be encouraged.
Recognizing that the Federation has only one percent of the
resources of the labor movement, assistance provided by the
AFLCIO will encourage and reward expanded commitment and spending
by unions and their regions and locals. A new Organizing Fund
will provide a range of support and assistance, strategically
applied.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../estatement.html">Executive Council Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
